Preheat your oven to 150 degrees. Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat and add a glug of @oil{}. Gently fry the @gnocchi{1000} until it is golden all over. This should take around ~{10%minutes}. Stir frequently to make sure it doesn't burn.

> Do this in batches and when one batch is ready, keep it warm on a #baking tray{} in the oven whilst you get on with the next batch.

Cut the @plum tomatoes{1} in half through the equator and pop into a bowl. Drizzle over a glug of @oil{} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Keep to one side. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Cut the top and bottom off the @courgette{1} and cut in half lengthways. Cut each half into three long strips, then chop at 1cm intervals to create small chunks.

Pop a #saucepan{} on medium heat and add a splash of @oil{}. Add the @chorizo{2}(diced) and cook for ~{5%minutes} until it is browned and has released its lovely red oil.

Once your chorizo is cooked, add your garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} over medium-high heat and then add the @chicken stock pot{1/2} and the @water{100}. Stir to dissolve your stock pot and bring to the boil.

When the water is boiling, add your courgette and @baby spinach{1}. Cover the pan with a #lid{} or #plate{} and cook for ~{4-5%minutes} until your spinach is wilted.

Next, pull the @basil{1}(leaves pulled off stalks and roughly chopped) leaves off their stalks and then roughly chop. Add half to your tomatoes and mix well.

When your courgette and spinach are cooked, mix in the @crème fraîche{1} and bring to the boil. This is your creamy sauce. Stir in the leftover basil and add @salt{} and @black pepper{} to taste.

Add your gnocchi to your creamy sauce. Spoon your creamy gnocchi into #bowls{} and finish with your tomatoes on top. Enjoy